2019-12-17 08:02:54	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> Hmm is there a way I can take a certain amount of steps in an iterator block? `next` will only go once, and I'd like to skip over some things without having to test them
2019-12-17 08:04:03	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> for example ⏎  ⏎ ```code paste, see link``` [https://gitter.im/crystal-lang/crystal?at=5df8ee620616d6515e55d53a]
2019-12-17 08:07:42	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> I can come up with a way how to do this with an iterator without the block
2019-12-17 08:07:48	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> but this reads a lot better
2019-12-17 08:08:35	FromGitter	<Blacksmoke16> `next if num >= 10 && num <= 19`
2019-12-17 08:08:55	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> but that involves testing those cases
2019-12-17 08:09:22	FromGitter	<Blacksmoke16> maybe just remove those numbers before iterating then
2019-12-17 08:09:52	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> I won't know what to remove without iterating with the guard clause
2019-12-17 08:10:51	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> I just want to be able to skip over x amount of times in an iterator, since I'll know in advance they'll fail the check
2019-12-17 08:11:12	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> but only once reaching the one before it
2019-12-17 08:11:55	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> I don't think there's a way
2019-12-17 08:30:23	FromGitter	<alehander92> is the problem in performance
2019-12-17 08:30:30	FromGitter	<alehander92> or just in code elegance
2019-12-17 08:43:12	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> both?
2019-12-17 08:43:39	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> in my limited case, performance doesn't matter, but it'd be a nice thing to have in my toolkit for when performance does matter
2019-12-17 08:48:31	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> https://carc.in/#/r/87q4
2019-12-17 08:48:34	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> like this... is ugly
2019-12-17 09:04:04	FromGitter	<kinxer> @Daniel-Worrall https://carc.in/#/r/87qc ?
2019-12-17 09:04:38	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> that's still testing the cases
2019-12-17 09:04:42	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> and iterating twice
2019-12-17 09:05:20	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> Does any lang even have the feature I'm thinking of lol
2019-12-17 09:06:31	FromGitter	<kinxer> Is it iterating twice? I thought iterators evaluated lazily.
2019-12-17 09:07:45	FromGitter	<kinxer> They seem much less useful if they don't.
2019-12-17 09:08:26	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> well it's iterating once to know what to reject, then iterating again to print
2019-12-17 09:11:07	FromGitter	<kinxer> I had assumed it was rejecting as it iterated in `#each`, which is what I expect and want from an iterator.
2019-12-17 09:11:43	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> you gave it 2 blocks
2019-12-17 09:12:08	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> so I *think* it's twice
2019-12-17 09:12:19	FromGitter	<kinxer> ```code paste, see link``` [https://gitter.im/crystal-lang/crystal?at=5df8fe63f1cc6c27ea66848a]
2019-12-17 09:12:24	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> the important part is that it's still testing those elements
2019-12-17 09:12:46	FromGitter	<kinxer> Calling `Iterator#reject` wraps the iterator in this struct.
2019-12-17 09:12:58	FromGitter	<kinxer> So it does check as it iterates.
2019-12-17 09:13:06	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> ah, okay
2019-12-17 09:13:22	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> but it would still check
2019-12-17 09:14:02	FromGitter	<kinxer> Yeah, it's going to do the check on every element, but that's true in https://carc.in/#/r/87q4, too.
2019-12-17 09:15:04	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> I don't think so, it'll call next 10 times without making the conditional check
2019-12-17 09:15:30	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> What I'm thinking is if the conditional is an expensive calculation, I want to skip over as many as I can
2019-12-17 09:15:33	FromGitter	<kinxer> Ah, that's true.
2019-12-17 09:16:01	FromGitter	<kinxer> So there could be a performance penalty if you're skipping a ton of elements and/or the check is really expensive.
2019-12-17 09:16:35	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> `next` gets the next element, which I'd prefer to avoid too.
2019-12-17 09:17:50	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> I could probably write a function on iterator that does what I want actually
2019-12-17 09:19:07	FromGitter	<kinxer> I mean, it seems like a reasonable use case for`Enumerable` to skip the `n`th element to the `m`th element.
2019-12-17 09:19:34	FromGitter	<kinxer> In an ideal world, it would never be necessary because all inputs would be well-formed and useful, but that's not the world we live in.
2019-12-17 09:20:51	FromGitter	<alehander92> but you can always do something like each_with_index and do a cheap check
2019-12-17 09:21:13	FromGitter	<alehander92> probably possible to make more elegant with some abstraction
